ğŸ”¹ What is a Source File in C++?
A source file in C++ is a file where we write our C++ code. This file has a .cpp extension, 
and it contains instructions for the computer to perform tasks like calculations, 
printing text, or making games! ğŸ®

ğŸ”¹ Types of C++ Files
In C++, we work with three main file types:

File Type	Extension	Purpose
Source File	.cpp	Contains the actual C++ code
Header File	.h	Contains function declarations & reusable code
Object File	.o or .obj	Machine code generated after compilation
So, the source file (.cpp) is where you write all your logic. ğŸ“

ğŸ”¹ Whatâ€™s Inside a Source File?
A C++ source file usually contains these sections:

1ï¸âƒ£ Preprocessor Directives (Libraries ğŸ“š)
ğŸ‘‰ These tell the compiler to include external code (like iostream for input/output).

#include <iostream>  // Includes the iostream library for input & output
ğŸ’¡ Why? Because iostream lets us use cin (input) and cout (output).

2ï¸âƒ£ Namespace Declaration
ğŸ‘‰ This makes writing code easier by allowing us to avoid writing std:: all the time.
                                using namespace std;
ğŸ’¡ Without it, youâ€™d have to write:
                             std::cout << "Hello World!";
Instead of:
                              cout << "Hello World!";
3ï¸âƒ£ The main() Function (Entry Point ğŸ¯)
ğŸ‘‰ Every C++ program must have a main() function. Itâ€™s where execution starts!

       int main() {
           cout << "Hello, C++!" << endl;  // Prints a message
            return 0;  // Ends the program
       }

ğŸ’¡ Why? Without main(), the compiler wouldnâ€™t know where to start running your program!

4ï¸âƒ£ Variables & Data (Memory Storage ğŸ’¾)
ğŸ‘‰ We store data inside variables.
                int age = 25;  // Stores a number
                string name = "Alice";  // Stores text
ğŸ’¡ Why? Variables help us store, modify, and use data in our program.

5ï¸âƒ£ Functions (Reusable Code ğŸ› ï¸)
ğŸ‘‰ Functions let us organize our code into reusable blocks.
            void greet() {
                cout << "Welcome to C++!" << endl;
            }
            int main() {
                greet();  // Calling the function
                return 0;
            }
ğŸ’¡ Why? Instead of repeating code, we create a function once and use it many times!

6ï¸âƒ£ Object-Oriented Programming (OOP ğŸ­)
ğŸ‘‰ C++ supports Classes & Objects to structure code.
            class Car {
                public:
                string brand;
                void honk() {
                    cout << "Beep beep!" << endl;
                }
            };

            int main() {
                Car myCar;  // Create an object
                myCar.brand = "Toyota";
                myCar.honk();  // Call method
                return 0;
            }

ğŸ’¡ Why? OOP makes code organized, reusable, and modular.
ğŸ”¹ Source File Compilation Process ğŸ”„
Your .cpp file cannot be directly executed! It must go through three steps:

Step	Process	Tool
1ï¸âƒ£ Preprocessing	Handles #include & #define	Preprocessor
2ï¸âƒ£ Compilation	Converts .cpp into .o/.obj	Compiler (GCC, MSVC, Clang)
3ï¸âƒ£ Linking	Combines files into .exe	Linker

Example using GCC (Linux/Mac/WSL):
    g++ myprogram.cpp -o myprogram
    ./myprogram  # Run the program
Example using MSVC (Windows, Visual Studio Command Prompt):
    cl myprogram.cpp
    myprogram.exe  # Run the program

ğŸ”¹ Summary of a Source File ğŸš€
âœ” It stores the actual code in a .cpp file.
âœ” It has preprocessor directives, functions, variables, and OOP concepts.
âœ” It must be compiled before it can run.
âœ” It works with header files (.h) and object files (.o).

ğŸ”¹ Example: A Complete Source File
      #include <iostream>  // Preprocessor Directive
      using namespace std;  // Avoids writing std::

      class Animal {  // OOP Class
          public:
          string name;
          void speak() {
                cout << name << " says Hello!" << endl;
          }
      };

      int main() {  // Entry Point
          Animal cat;
          cat.name = "Whiskers";
          cat.speak();  // Calls a method
          return 0;
      }

ğŸ”¹ Output:
Whiskers says Hello!

